  { id: uuidv4(), name: "Men", description: `1. Outline: Men, also known as the Second Children of Ilúvatar, are a race created by Eru Ilúvatar. They appeared after the Elves in Arda and are also referred to as 'Edain', meaning 'The Second People'. Their arrival was prophesied by Ilúvatar, and they brought significant changes to the history and fate of Arda. 2.1. History-Origin Men are the second children of Eru Ilúvatar, born from his thoughts. They are referred to as 'Edain', and their appearance was prophesied by Eru Ilúvatar. They appeared after Ilúvatar created Arda, and their existence brought significant changes to the destiny of Arda. 2.2. Men and the World Men played a significant role in Arda. They developed various races and cultures, and some of them became rulers of Arda. Through their free will, they significantly influenced the history of Arda. They established powerful kingdoms, waged great wars, and ultimately played a crucial role in determining the fate of Arda. 2.3. The Line of Númenor Some of the Men inherited the blood of the Elves of Arda by marrying them, becoming Númenóreans. They greatly influenced the history of Arda with their abilities and wisdom. The lineage of the Númenóreans impacted many human kingdoms of Arda, and their descendants played a crucial role in determining the history and fate of Arda. 3. Etymology The term 'Edain' is Elvish, meaning 'The Second People'. This term reflects the fact that they were the later-appearing children of Ilúvatar in Arda. The term "Second Children" reflects the fact that they appeared after the Elves, the first children of Ilúvatar.` },
  // 1
  { id: uuidv4(), name: "Elf", description: `1. Outline: Elves, also known as the First Children of Ilúvatar, are a race created by Eru Ilúvatar. Being the first to awake in Arda, they are also referred to as 'Quendi', meaning 'Those that speak with voices'. Their awakening was the first major event in the history of Arda, and they played a significant role in shaping its destiny. 2.1. History-Origin Elves are the first children of Eru Ilúvatar, born from his thoughts. They are referred to as 'Quendi', and their awakening was the first significant event in the history of Arda. They appeared before Men and their existence brought significant changes to the destiny of Arda. 2.2. Elves and the World Elves played a significant role in Arda. They developed various cultures and kingdoms, and some of them became the greatest craftsmen and warriors of Arda. Through their long lives, they significantly influenced the history of Arda. They fought against Morgoth, the first Dark Lord, and played a crucial role in the wars of the First Age. 2.3. The Line of the Half-elven Some of the Elves intermarried with Men, producing the half-elven line. Half-elves had the choice of being mortal or immortal, and their descendants played a crucial role in the history and fate of Arda. Notably, Elrond chose to be an Elf, while his brother Elros chose to be a Man and became the first King of Númenor. 3. Etymology The term 'Quendi' is an Elvish word, meaning 'Those that speak with voices'. This term reflects the fact that they were the first race in Arda to speak. The term 'First Children' reflects the fact that they were the first beings awakened by Eru Ilúvatar in the world of Arda.` },
  // 2
  { id: uuidv4(), name: "Dwarf", description: `1. Outline General Introduction The Dwarves, also known as the Khazâd, are a race in J.R.R. Tolkien's Middle-earth, known for their skills in mining and crafting. They were created by Aulë, one of the Valar, out of impatience and desire for the arrival of the Children of Ilúvatar (Elves and Men). 2.1. History-Origin Aulë created the Dwarves out of stone in the depths of Middle-earth, but as he had limited understanding of the Children of Ilúvatar, Dwarves were initially lifeless. When Ilúvatar confronted Aulë about his creation, Aulë offered to destroy the Dwarves. But Ilúvatar, moved by Aulë's humility and love for his creations, granted them life and free will. However, Ilúvatar decreed that Dwarves could only awaken after the Elves. 2.2. Dwarves and the World Dwarves are known for their craft and mining skills, their love of mountains and precious minerals, especially gold. They are a hardy race, resistant to many diseases and able to endure physical hardship. Dwarves are typically shorter and sturdier than Men and Elves. They live much longer than Men, with lifespans of over 250 years. Dwarves are also known for their strong sense of kinship and loyalty to their clans, which are traced through the paternal line. Seven clans of Dwarves are mentioned in Tolkien's work: Longbeards, Firebeards, Broadbeams, Ironfists, Stiffbeards, Blacklocks, and Stonefoots. 2.3. Notable Dwarves Among the many Dwarves in Tolkien's work, some of the most notable include Thorin Oakenshield, leader of the Company of Dwarves in "The Hobbit"; Gimli, a member of the Fellowship of the Ring; and Balin, a friend of Bilbo Baggins who later attempted to reclaim Moria, the ancestral home of the Dwarves. 3. Etymology "Dwarves" is the modern English word used by Tolkien to represent the race known as the Khazâd in their own language, Khuzdul, which was created by Aulë at the same time as the Dwarves. The singular form is "Dwarf". The term "Dwarf" comes from Old English 'dweorg', which has cognates in Old Norse 'dvergr' and Old High German 'twerg'. It is unclear what the original meaning of the word was in these older languages.` },
  // 3
  { id: uuidv4(), name: "Hobbit", description: `1. Outline General Introduction Hobbits, also known as Halflings, are a peaceful and agrarian race residing mainly in the Shire and Bree in Middle-earth in J.R.R. Tolkien's universe. They are known for their love of comfort, food, and a quiet, unadventurous life. They are smaller in stature than Men and Elves, averaging between 2 to 4 feet tall. 2.1. History-Origin The exact origin of Hobbits is not clear, though they are considered a branch of Men rather than a separate race. They migrated from the east into the region of the Shire, which they have inhabited for many centuries. The Hobbits' simple and rustic life shields them from the dangerous events unfolding in the wider world of Middle-earth. 2.2. Hobbits and the World Hobbits are excellent farmers and gardeners, and they have a particular love for smoking pipe-weed, a habit they introduced to Men. They live in hole-dwellings known as "smials" or in houses similar to those of Men. Hobbits are also known for their stealth and quietness, being able to move silently and unseen when they wish. There are three main types of Hobbits: Harfoots, Stoors, and Fallohides. Harfoots are the most common; they are shorter and browner and have closer relations with Dwarves. Stoors are broader and heavier and have an affinity for water, boats, and swimming. Fallohides are the least numerous, taller and fairer, friendlier with Elves, and lovers of trees and woodland. 2.3. Notable Hobbits Notable Hobbits in Tolkien's work include Bilbo Baggins, the protagonist of "The Hobbit," who becomes involved in the quest to reclaim the Lonely Mountain from the dragon Smaug; Frodo Baggins, the main character of "The Lord of the Rings," who is entrusted with the task of destroying the One Ring; and Samwise Gamgee, Frodo's loyal friend and companion on his journey. 3. Etymology The term "Hobbit" is said to come from the Rohirric Holbytla, meaning "hole-dweller." The word "Hobbit" was invented by J.R.R. Tolkien. The origin of the word in the context of Tolkien's world is unknown. The singular form is "Hobbit," and the plural form is "Hobbits."` },
  // 4
  { id: uuidv4(), name: "Orc", description: `1. Outline General Introduction Orcs, often called Goblins in "The Hobbit", are a race of creatures in J.R.R. Tolkien's Middle-earth. They are typically associated with evil, serving as soldiers and minions of darker powers, such as Morgoth and Sauron. They are known for their cruelty, hatred, and fear of beautiful things. 2.1. History-Origin The precise origin of Orcs is a subject of much debate and uncertainty within Tolkien's works. The most widely accepted theory is that they were once Elves, captured and corrupted by the first Dark Lord, Morgoth. He twisted them through dark magic into the hateful and malicious creatures known as Orcs. 2.2. Orcs and the World Orcs are often found in the service of evil powers. They are known for their strength and brutality, and they are skilled in the creation of weapons and war machines. They generally live in harsh conditions, such as mountains, caves, and the dark lands of Mordor. They are said to be cannibalistic and have a strong hatred for Elves and Men. Orcs vary greatly in appearance, intelligence, and strength. Some are small and weak, while others, like the Uruk-hai, are large, powerful, and capable of moving under the sun - a trait not common to most Orcs. 2.3. Notable Orcs There are several notable Orcs in Tolkien's work. Azog, an Orc chieftain who killed Thror, the grandfather of Thorin Oakenshield, plays a significant role in the history of the Dwarves. Gollum, originally a Stoorish Hobbit named Sméagol, was corrupted by the One Ring and developed some Orc-like characteristics. 3. Etymology The term "Orc" comes from Old English and originally meant "demon" or "ogre." In Tolkien's world, the term is used to refer to the various species of evil creatures, including Goblins. The singular form is "Orc," and the plural form is "Orcs." The term "Uruk-hai" translates to "Orc-folk" in the Black Speech, a language invented by Sauron.` },
  // 5
  { id: uuidv4(), name: "Balrog", description: `1. Outline General Introduction Balrogs, also known as the Valaraukar, are a race of powerful, demonic beings in J.R.R. Tolkien's Middle-earth. They are associated with fire and shadow and are often depicted as large, menacing creatures with the ability to manipulate both elements. They serve as some of the most fearsome servants of the first Dark Lord, Morgoth. 2.1. History-Origin Balrogs were originally Maiar, a race of divine spirits who assisted the Valar in shaping the world. However, they were corrupted by Morgoth, the first Dark Lord, and became his most loyal and terrifying servants. They played a significant role in his war against the Elves and Men during the First Age of Middle-earth. 2.2. Balrogs and the World Balrogs are known for their immense strength, fire manipulation, and the terror they invoke. They are said to wield fiery whips and swords, and their mere presence can fill the air with darkness and heat. They mainly dwell in the deep places of the earth, such as the underground realm of Moria. There is debate about the number of Balrogs, as Tolkien's writings suggest different figures. However, it is generally accepted that they were few but extremely powerful. 2.3. Notable Balrogs The most famous Balrog is Durin's Bane, who dwelt in the Mines of Moria. It was this Balrog that Gandalf the Grey encountered and battled on the Bridge of Khazad-dûm, a confrontation that resulted in both of their deaths, though Gandalf was later resurrected. 3. Etymology The term "Balrog" comes from the Elvish language Quenya, in which "Valarauko" (plural "Valaraukar") means "Demon of Might." In Sindarin, another Elvish language, it is "Belryg" (plural "Belryg"). The singular form is "Balrog," and the plural form is "Balrogs."` },
  // 6
  { id: uuidv4(), name: "Dragon", description: `1. Outline General Introduction Dragons in J.R.R. Tolkien's Middle-earth are fearsome and cunning creatures known for their immense size, fiery breath, and avaricious nature. They are often associated with evil, with many serving Morgoth, the first Dark Lord, during the First Age. 2.1. History-Origin The exact origin of dragons is not explicitly stated in Tolkien's works. However, it is generally accepted that they were created by Morgoth during the First Age. Their creation was one of Morgoth's most heinous acts, embodying his corruption and destructive power. 2.2. Dragons and the World Dragons are known for their destructive power, immense wisdom, and insatiable greed. They often hoard treasure, especially gold and precious gems. There are different types of dragons, with some having the ability to fly and others possessing an impenetrable scaly hide. Some dragons also have the power of speech and are known for their cunning and persuasive speech. Dragons are primarily found in the North, with many dwelling in the Grey Mountains and the Withered Heath. They have had a significant impact on the world, causing widespread destruction and playing pivotal roles in various events. 2.3. Notable Dragons Several dragons are mentioned in Tolkien's works. Glaurung, the first of the dragons and known as the Father of Dragons, played a significant role in the tragic tale of Túrin Turambar. Another notable dragon is Smaug, the primary antagonist in "The Hobbit," who hoards a vast treasure in the Lonely Mountain until he is slain by Bard the Bowman. 3. Etymology The term "dragon" originates from the Greek word "drakon," meaning "large serpent" or "sea serpent". In Middle-earth, different types of dragons are often identified, such as "fire-drakes" (dragons that can breathe fire) and "cold-drakes" (dragons that cannot breathe fire). The terms can also distinguish between dragons that fly and those that do not.` },
  // 7
  { id: uuidv4(), name: "Ainur", description: `1. Outline General Introduction The Ainur, also known as the "Holy Ones," are the first beings created by Eru Ilúvatar, the supreme being in J.R.R. Tolkien's Middle-earth. They are divine spirits that exist outside the physical world and are divided into two main groups: the Valar and the Maiar. 2.1. History-Origin The Ainur were brought into existence by Ilúvatar through the Music of the Ainur, a cosmic composition that also conceived the world. After the creation of the world, many Ainur descended into it to guide and shape its destiny, thus becoming the Valar and Maiar. 2.2. Ainur and the World The Valar are the most powerful of the Ainur and are often referred to as the Powers of the World. They are responsible for shaping the world and governing its fundamental aspects, like the sea, sky, earth, and underworld. The Maiar are lesser Ainur who serve the Valar. They often act as their servants, messengers, and helpers. Some Maiar are associated with specific Valar, while others serve the whole pantheon. 2.3. Notable Ainur Among the Valar, some of the most notable include Manwë, the lord of the Valar; Varda, the queen of the stars; Ulmo, the lord of waters; and Melkor, who later became Morgoth, the first Dark Lord. Notable Maiar include Gandalf, Saruman, and Radagast, who are known as the Istari or wizards, and Sauron, who later became the second Dark Lord. 3. Etymology The term "Ainur" comes from Quenya, an Elvish language invented by Tolkien, and means "Holy Ones." The singular form is "Ainu." The term "Valar" means "Powers of the World," and the singular form is "Vala." The term "Maiar" is the plural form and means "the Beautiful," with the singular form being "Maia."` }
